<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> take it on the nose • take it through the nose</xh5><p> <i>take it on the nose</i>—(sl.) meet misfortune or defeat courageously <i>(also: take it on the chin):</i> And as the 1980s saw labor <u>take it on the nose</u> when choosing to strike, so the late 1990s have been an era of high-stakes labor wins.</p><p> <i>take it through the nose</i>—(U.S. Drug users) inhale cocaine: He went into the john, and most of us knew he had to <u>take it through the nose</u> right then.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>pay through the nose</b>—<i>pay too much for smth.: </i>It’s a terrible car, and what annoys me is that I <u>paid through the nose</u> for it.</p> </entry>
